==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*wōda-'', from Indo-European ''*wāt-'' ‘prophet’.  Cognate with Middle Dutch [[woet]] (Dutch [[woede]]), Old High German [[wuot]] (German [[Wut]] ‘fury’), Old Norse [[óðr]], Gothic [[𐍅𐍉𐌸𐍃]] ‘demonically possessed’.  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[vates]] ‘seer, prophet’, Irish [[fáith]] ‘poet’, Welsh [[gwawd]] ‘song’.

